Choosing data from EVDS

For the analysis, the data is chosen as monthly and for three years period.Car purchases (araç satın alımı) from customer price index category “TP.FG.J071” is chosen and named as “Car_Purchasing_Index”. Car rental, sales,spare parts data (araç kiralama/satış/yedek parça), which is coded in EVDS as “TP.KKHARTUT.KT3”, from bank and credit cards spendings (banka kartı ve kredi kartı harcama tutarı(bin tl)) category is chosen and names as “Car_Rental_and_Sales”. Lastly, the manufactured vehicle (binek araç üretimi) data “TP.UR.S08” is chosen from the production category and named as “Manufactured_Automobile_Number”. The relation between car purchases, credit card spendings for car expenses and total produced car is investigated.

Analysis

When plotting car purchases, credit card spendings for car expenses and total produced car data, all data has varying numbers so that it may not give a clear analysis. However, Car_Rental_and_Sales(blue) data and Manufactured_Automobile_Number(green) has correlation and both has a stable trend from the grah above. The Car_Purchasing_Index(red) data has more fluctuating trend according to the plot. To have better analysis, the graphs are plotted separately because all categories have different data ranges in the specific dates.

Detailed analysis of data

As it can be seen from the above graphs, there is no parallel trend between Car_Rental_and_Sales(blue) data and Manufactured_Automobile_Number(green) data. However, from the 4th month of 2020, vehicle production is increasing and credit card spendings on car expenses (Car_Rental_and_Sales) data is also increasing similarly. One reason for this increase may be the pandemic because people tend to live individually after the pandemic risk. Therefore, the tendency to buy vehicles may result in an increase of vehicle production. When comparing the car purchases and the credit card spendings on car expenses data both of them have an increasing trend, especially from the 4th month of 2020. So it can be inferred that there is a relation between three data and this may be due to covid-19 pandemic.

Google trends analysis key word choices

Each data category is compared with the key word searched in Google trends. The key words chosen for each data set is as follows: “araba kredi” key word is chosen for bank an credit card spendigns for car rental, sales, spare parts expenses, “araba fiyatları” key word is chosen for car purchases, “araba” key word is chosen for the manufactured vehicle data.

Reading and arranging data

The data downloaded from Google trends page is weekly, but the EVDS data is monthly so Google trends data is re-arranged as monthly and the mean of the search key word is gathered. car loan (araba kredi) data, car price (araba fiyatları) data and car (araba) data is arranged below, respectively.

Results of the analysis

The car purchases data (of consumer price index) has a parallel increasing trend with bank and credit card spendings on car expenses. The relation makes sense because the increase in car prices increases the tendency to spend with bank and credit cards. Moreover, the manufacured car number increase results from the increase in credit card spendings on car expenses. The increase from the beginning of 2020 in all three data may due to the pandemic because people give more importance to their health and decide to provide their transportation with their own cars, for the health issues.

For the Google trends analysis, there is no clear relation found with the key word “araba”, although it is expected to increase due to the manufactured car number. “Araba fiyatları” key word search rate shows an opposite trend with car purchases of consumer price index data. The reason is that if the car purchases of consumer price index increases, people tend not to buy cars so that “araba fiyatları” search ratings decrease. Finally, when “araba kredi” search rate and the bank and credit card spendings of car rental, sales, spare parts expenses, both data has fluctuating trend but goes parallel to each other. Both data are increasing from 2018 to 2020 and there is a sharp decrease at 2020. This may due to an increase in the car prices.
